%I A394655 #11 Mar 30 2026 12:44:38
%S A394655 1,2,6,12,60,60,420,6720,20160,20160,221760,221760,2882880,2882880,
%T A394655 2882880,184504320,3136573440,3136573440,59594895360,59594895360,
%U A394655 59594895360,59594895360,1370682593280,1370682593280,6853412966400,6853412966400,555126450278400
%N A394655 a(n) is the least common recursive multiple of {1, ..., n}.
%C A394655 See A287958 for the definition of a recursive multiple.
%C A394655 The sequence increases only when n belongs to A164336 \ {1}, say n = p_1 ^ ... ^ p_k for k > 0 prime numbers p_1, ..., p_k; in that case, the prime tower factorization of a(n) equals that of a(n-1) plus an extra leaf p_k (see illustration in Links section).
%H A394655 Rémy Sigrist, <a href="/A394655/b394655.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..255</a>
%H A394655 Rémy Sigrist, <a href="/A394655/a394655.pdf">Illustration of initial terms</a>
%H A394655 <a href="/index/Lc#lcm">Index entries for sequences related to lcm's</a>
%F A394655 a(n) = A287958(a(n-1), n) for n > 1.
%F A394655 a(n) >= A003418(n).
%e A394655 See Links section.
%o A394655 (PARI) A287958(n, k) = if (n*k==0, return (max(n, k))); my (g=factor(lcm(n, k))); return (prod(i=1, #g~, g[i, 1]^A287958(valuation(n, g[i, 1]), valuation(k, g[i, 1]))))
%o A394655 { v = 1; for (n = 1, 27, print1 (v = A287958(v, n)", ");); }
%Y A394655 Cf. A003418, A164336 (indices of records), A287958.
%K A394655 nonn
%O A394655 1,2
%A A394655 _Rémy Sigrist_, Mar 27 2026
